abstract  = {This working paper investigates the formative period of Israeli strategic culture by examining the contrasting worldviews and policy choices of David Ben-Gurion (the security hawk) and Moshe Sharett (the diplomatic moderate). We utilize process-tracing and biographical methods to show how their early debates and institutional struggles laid the foundation for the enduring tension between military assertiveness and diplomatic engagement in Israeli foreign policy. This paper is part of a larger project on leader hawkishness.},
